        "D": "Immediately cease all investigation activities and refuse to issue any report or findings"
      },
      "correct_answer": "B",
      "explanation": "When a fraud examiner discovers a relationship that could impair independence or create a conflict of interest, the ethical obligation is to disclose this information to appropriate parties (such as management, the board, or legal counsel) and discuss whether continued involvement is appropriate. This transparency allows for proper assessment of whether the relationship affects the examiner's ability to remain independent and objective. Simply softening findings (A) would compromise integrity, ignoring the relationship (C) fails to address the conflict, and immediately ceasing work (D) without disclosure and discussion is not the most appropriate first step.",
      "topic": "Independence and Conflicts of Interest",
      "subtopic": "Disclosure Obligations",
