    {
      "id": "S3D09-017",
      "question": "During a fraud examination, you discover that the subject of your investigation has made several large charitable donations to a legitimate nonprofit organization. The client asks you to characterize these donations as suspicious and potentially part of a money laundering scheme in your report, even though you have found no evidence to support this claim. What is the most ethical course of action?",
      "options": [
        "Include the charitable donations as suspicious activities since the client is paying for the investigation and has requested this information",
        "Omit any mention of the charitable donations from your report to avoid potential conflicts",
        "Report only the factual information about the donations without characterizing them as suspicious unless evidence supports such a conclusion",
        "Withdraw from the engagement immediately without providing any report to the client"
      ],
      "correct_answer": 2,
      "explanation": "The most ethical course of action is to report only factual information without unfounded characterizations. As a fraud examiner, you have a duty to be truthful and accurate in your reporting, regardless of client pressure. Including unsupported allegations would violate professional ethics and potentially harm an innocent party. Simply omitting relevant facts or withdrawing without cause are not appropriate solutions. The correct approach is to present the facts objectively and explain to the client that you cannot make unsupported claims, maintaining your integrity and professional independence.",
